// === AI Coding Memory Configuration Guide ===
//
// This configuration uses fine-grained shared knowledge spaces for optimal memory
// organization and automatic routing. The system automatically classifies and routes
// memories to appropriate knowledge spaces based on content type.
//
// === Fine-Grained Shared Knowledge Spaces ===
//
// The system uses 8 specialized shared knowledge spaces, automatically routing
// memories based on content type:
//
// 1. personal-prefs: Personal preferences, tool choices, work habits
//    → Entity types: Preference
//    → Examples: "User prefers dark mode", "User likes TypeScript"
//
// 2. std-coding: Coding standards, naming conventions, formatting rules
//    → Entity types: Convention
//    → Examples: "4-space indentation", "Use camelCase for variables"
//
// 3. std-design: Design standards, UI patterns, interaction principles
//    → Entity types: DesignPattern
//    → Examples: "Use Material Design", "Follow accessibility guidelines"
//
// 4. std-arch: Architecture standards, design patterns, technology choices
//    → Entity types: Architecture, Decision
//    → Examples: "Use microservices architecture", "Prefer REST over GraphQL"
//
// 5. proc-dev: Development procedures, Git workflows, code review processes
//    → Entity types: Procedure
//    → Examples: "Run tests before commit", "Code review required for PRs"
//
// 6. proc-test: Testing procedures, test strategies, quality standards
//    → Entity types: Procedure, TestPlan
//    → Examples: "Write unit tests for all functions", "Coverage target: 80%"
//
// 7. proc-product: Product procedures, requirement management, version planning
//    → Entity types: Procedure
//    → Examples: "Follow semantic versioning", "Update changelog for releases"
//
// 8. kb-tech: Technical knowledge base, API usage, best practices
//    → Entity types: Document, Topic
//    → Examples: "React Hooks best practices", "Docker optimization tips"
//
// === Knowledge Classification ===
//
// Shared Knowledge (Cross-project accessible):
//    - Automatically routed to appropriate shared groups based on content
//    - Accessible from all projects using the same shared_group_ids
//    - Examples: User preferences, coding standards, development procedures
//
// Project-Specific Knowledge:
//    - Stored only in the project's group_id
//    - Not accessible from other projects
//    - Examples: API endpoints, project-specific configurations, implementation details
//
// === Configuration Options ===
//
// a) shared_group_ids: List of fine-grained shared knowledge spaces
//    - Use the 8 predefined spaces for optimal organization
//    - System automatically routes memories to the correct space
//    - All projects using the same shared_group_ids can access shared knowledge
//
// b) shared_entity_types: Entity types that indicate shared knowledge
//    - Preference: User preferences (coding style, tool choices)
//    - Convention: Coding standards and naming conventions
//    - DesignPattern: UI patterns and design standards
//    - Architecture: Architecture decisions and patterns
//    - Procedure: Development and testing procedures
//    - Decision: Technical decisions and choices
//
// c) shared_patterns: Keywords that indicate shared knowledge
//    - Includes common terms in English and Chinese
//    - Used by rule-based classifier (write_strategy: "simple")
//    - Less important when using llm_based strategy
//
// d) write_strategy: Classification strategy
//    - "simple": Fast, rule-based (no extra LLM cost, less accurate)
//    - "llm_based": Intelligent classification with content splitting (recommended)
//
// === Strategy Comparison ===
//
// simple (Rule-Based):
//   Pros: Fast, zero extra LLM cost, predictable
//   Cons: Limited to predefined patterns, may miss nuanced content
//   Use case: Simple projects with clear patterns
//
// llm_based (LLM Classifier - RECOMMENDED):
//   Pros: More accurate, understands context, can split mixed content
//   Cons: Additional LLM API cost per classification
//   Use case: Complex projects with nuanced knowledge classification
//
// === Example: llm_based Content Splitting ===
//
// Input: "User prefers 4-space indentation. The API endpoint is at /api/v1/users."
//
// Output (automatically split):
//   - Shared: "User prefers 4-space indentation"
//     → Classified as: Convention
//     → Routed to: std-coding (shared group)
//     → Accessible from: All projects
//
//   - Project: "The API endpoint is at /api/v1/users"
//     → Classified as: PROJECT_SPECIFIC
//     → Routed to: my-coding-project (project group only)
//     → Accessible from: This project only
//
// === Relationship with Cursor Rules ===
//
// Cursor Rules (.cursor/rules/*.mdc):
//   - Static rules: Define when and how to use Graphiti tools
//   - Behavior guidance: Tell AI when to search/store memories
//   - Universal: Apply to all projects
//
// Graphiti Memory (this configuration):
//   - Dynamic knowledge: Stores actual user preferences and project knowledge
//   - Context provider: Provides personalized context for AI decisions
//   - Project-specific: Tailored to each project's needs
//
// Workflow:
//   1. Cursor Rules trigger: "User mentions preference"
//   2. AI calls add_memory: Stores preference to Graphiti
//   3. System auto-routes: Preference → personal-prefs (shared)
//   4. Future queries: All projects can access this preference
//
// === Minimal Configuration ===
//
// For a basic setup without shared knowledge:
//
// {
//   "group_id": "my-simple-project"
// }
//
// === Advanced Configuration ===
//
// For projects with custom shared knowledge spaces:
//
// {
//   "group_id": "my-app",
//   "shared_group_ids": ["team-standards", "company-policies"],
//   "shared_entity_types": ["Preference", "Procedure", "Requirement"],
//   "shared_patterns": ["convention", "workflow", "standard"],
//   "write_strategy": "llm_based"
// }
//
// Note: Using the 8 fine-grained shared groups (as in this example) is
// recommended for optimal knowledge organization and automatic routing.
